{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_broadwick_ver01/data/sn93065779/00279558236/1945081601/0327.xml":{"full_text":"LINCOLN COUNTY\u2019S FAVORITE FAMILY NEWSPAPER\nWar Cutbacks Point\nUp Reconversion Needs\nCompanies Posses Sufficient\nFunds For Peacetime Re\nconversion Output.\nBy AL JEDLICKA\nAlready cut 9 per cent under peak\nMarch levels, war production is\nscheduled for a further 23 per cent\nreduction during the remainder of\n1948, pointing up reconversion prob\nlems facing the nation following the\ndefeat of Germany.\nTotalling 16.3 billion dollars, cut-'\nbacks during the first six months of 1\n1945 have affected 2,500 plants, but|\nwhereas many workers remained un\ntouched because much of the reduc\ntion was in future contracts rather\nthan in actual work, the situation will\ntend to reverse itself during the last\ntw 0 quarters of the year when pres\nent programs peter off.\nIndicative of the trend, 31 per cent\nof the contracts cut back in April\nwere for scheduled future production,\nwith the total for May 14 per cent. I\nIn June, however, the figure was only\n6 per cent, with the remainder con- j\nsisting of working contracts. j\nEven us the Senate was asked to 1\nact on liberalization of unemployment j\nlegislation to absord reconversion dis\ntress, and there were rumblings that\nthe whole reconversion program was\nmoving too slowly, OPA took steps!\nto facilitate manufacturers\u2019 switch\nover to civilian output and the Se\ncurities and Exchange commission re\nvealed that American corporations\nwith issues listed on the national\nstock exchanges possessed 63 per cent\nmore working capital than in 1939.\nIn seeking to speed up manufac\nturers\u2019 reconversion, OPA formulat\ned price policie s designed to guaran- j\ntee the producers an adequate profit\nmargin while at the same time keep-\ning costs within reasonable levels to\navert the danger of inflation.\nUnder the OPA plan, manufactur\ners doing an annual business of S2OO,- i\n000 or more will be permitted to add\nwage and material cost increases':\nover prewar prices, and then include I'\nhalf of the industry-wide profit mar-!\ngin for 1936 to 1939. I,\nFirms with an annual $50,000 to 1\n$200,000 business will follow the\nsame procedure for determining\ncosts, but will be allowed t 0 substi- I\nN. C. FIRST GRADEj\nGAS, 2IV2C Gallon\nJ i\nRECAPPING A SPECIALTY J\nt We have a complete new set of J\nJ Bacon Recap Molds and invite you t\nt to visit us and see this new equip- J\nJ ment. 1\n5 McGinnis bros. j\n{N. Aspen St. Linrolnton, N. C. J\nJ PHONE 382 J\nBan McGinnis\u2014Vaughn McGinnis J\nFOR SALE i\nDRAIN TILE S\nAND g\nFITTINGS\nSETH LUMBER CO. I\nINCORPORATED\nPhone 39\nMALARIA\nCHECKED IN 7 DAYS WITH\nLIQUID for\nMALARIAL\nSYMPTOMS\nTake only\ndirected.\nEach ingredient in every\nCleveland\nFeed\nis there for a purpose\u2014That purpose is to\nhelp you get the most eggs or milk or meat,\nand to maintain the health of the fowl or\nanimals fed.\n\nThere are no fillers in\nCLEVELAND FEEDS\n\nEagle Roller\nMill Co.\nSHELBY, N. C.\ntute their own 1936 to 1939 profit\nmargin instead of half of that for\ntheir particular industry.\nIn the case of businesse s with a\nyearly volume of less than $50,000,\nthey may use their current costs as\na base and then add their own prof\n-1 it margin for 1939, or, if that is not\navailable, then the net for 1940 or\ni 1941.\nTo help sjjeed the manufacturers\nalong, OPA will pass upon final\nI F r i c e s se t U P by companies doing\n,1 an annual business of $200,000 or\nmore, while the charges of the small\ner firms will be considered approved\nunless OPA notifie s them otherwise\nwithin 15 days.\nIn revealing that 1,209 American\ncorporations listed on the nation\u2019s\nstock exchanges possessed 63 per\ncent more working capital than in\n1939, the Securities and Exchange\ncommission indicated that U. S. in\ndustry was well heeled for the cost\nof switching production from u/ar to\nj peace.\nI Listed as $20,258,000,000 for the\nj L 290 aforesaid corporations, total\nI assets of all companies was estimated\njat $45,500,000,000.\nI In reviewing the finances of the\nj 1,290 corporations, the SEC reported\nI that the net working capital of 25\naircraft and related equipment com\npanies jumped from $79,000,000 in\n1939 to $470,000,000 in 1944, while\nthe liquid assets of 84 railroads\nsoared from $347,000,000 to $1,548,-\n000,000.\nWith half of the firms engaged in\nwar work, 837 manufacturing cor\nporations showed increases in work-\nI ing capital from $9,669,000,000 in\n1939 to $15,167,000,000.\nAnalyzing the working capital, the\nSEC reported that nearly one-third\nof the liquid assets consists of cash\non hand and in banks, and about one\nfifth in U. S. tax and savings notes.\nHoldings of U. S. government se\ncurities jumped from 846,000,000 in\n1939 to $6,663,000,000 in 1944, repre\nsenting about one-fourth of the total\nworking capital at the end of 1944.\nMeanwhile, holdings of other market\nable securities dropped from $491,- 1\n000,000 in 1939 to $361,000,000.\nStill anticipating widespread dis\ntress during reconversion despite 1\ngovernment efforts to remove re- i\nstrictive barriers to quick turnover to\ncivilian production, Sen. Harley Kil- i\ngore (D-W Va) asked Congress to\nliberalize grants to the unemployed\nto help tide them over the period.\nUnder Kilgore\u2019s proposed legisla-\ntion, federal, maritime and agricul\ntural processing workers would be\nincluded in unemployment compensa\ntion payments, along with workers\nin plants with less than eight per\nsons. At the same time, the federal\ngovernment would pitch in the dis- 1\nference to bring unemployment com- 1\npensation payments of the state g up\nto a level of $25 for 26 weeks. Sin- I\ngle vets would be allowed $25 and\nthose with dependents S3O for 52\nweeks. To aid persons stranded in 1\nidle war production centers, the U.\nS. would provide transportation ex-\npense to new jobs in other cities.\nWhile Kilgore appealed for liber- 1\nalized unemployment payments, fig\nures revealed that many Americans\nhave been looking ahead for postwar\nstress, with savings for the first I\nthree months of 1945 estimated at i\n$8,500,000,000. Os this, almost $5,- i\n000,000,000 was deposited in banks;\n$1,500,000,000 in U. S. bonds; $1,000,-\n000,000 in national service life in- s\nsurance, and $900,000,000 for private 1\npremiums. At the same time, con- 1\nsumer debt was cut $200,000,000 ex-\nelusive of mortgage obligations. 1\n\nMany serious accidents have re-\nsuited from carelessness with insec- 1\nticides used in the home and in the\ngarden.\nBE SURE AND READ THE ADS\ntoday. They pay big dividends.\nTHE LINCOLN TIMES, LINCOIJTTON, N. C\u201e THURSDAY, AUG. 16, 1945.\nFoe\u2019s Tricks Fooled\nYanks At First\nYanks in the Pacific often were\nj taken off-guard by unheard-of ruses.\nAmong them:\nThe Japanese sometimes called out\ncommands in English to confuse the\nAmericans. Some, after listening\nnearby, would shout out the name\nof an individual. When the GI or\n1 Marine appeared, he wa s shot.\nThe enemy soldiers used the white\ntruce flag to advance close to Amer\nican lines for combat purposes.\nEven when badly hurt, they fre\nquently slipped hand grenades from\ntheir clothing, hurling them at the\nU. S. medicos who had sped to their\naid. j\nBooby traps, fastened to dead Al\nlied and Nipponese fighters, were\nfused to explode when the tody was\nmoved.\nAnd with each campaign, the wily\nJapanese had new surprises in store.\n\u00a7lll\nWashington, D. C. (NWNS) \u2014Al-\nthough the defeat of Winston\nChurchill\u2019s Conservative party in\nEngland came as a seveie shock to\ngovernment leaders here, it is not\nexpected that the victory of the La\nbor party will alter Great Britain\u2019s\ninternational policies. For despite]\nthe wide difference in the domestic\ngoals of the different parties in Eng\nland, all are believed to be in agree\nment on foreign policy. Consequent\nly there is little danger of any re\nlaxation on the part of the English\ngovernment in waging the war\nagainst Japan or in agreeing t 0 the\nterms of the Charter written in Sanl\nFrancisco.\nAlthough the Charter has met with\nlittle opposition in our Senate, it is\nfeared that there may be many bat-'\nties over it when the time comes to!\ncarry out its purposes. For, although\nmost senators think there is no ques\ntion but that it commits our country\nto have troops and planes on call for\ninternational police duty, the group\nof isolationist senators led by Sen\nator Wheeler will not admit that we\nare so committed without passing\nseparate legislation. They also will\nnot admit that approval of the Char\nter gives the President power to use\ntroops, without approval by Con\ngress.\n\nEach week sees the relaxation of\nmore government control which bring\nus closer, step by step, to normal i\ncivilian life. The War Production]\nboard says that reconversion plans\nare progressing rapidly in many lead-1\ning industries and that more and\nmore products will return to the mar-1;\nket as materials become available.\nThe fact that war production orders\nwere reduced by an overall total of\nabout $3,500,000,000 in June gives]]\nsome indication of the amount of\nsupplies and manpower, formerly i\nused for war purposes, which are\nnow available for home use. I\nAmong the products on which the]\nWPB says reconversion progress is\nparticularly outstanding are automo- 1\nbiles, refrigerators, vacuum cleaners, i\nsewing machines, stoves, plumbing\nand heating equipment, and electri- i\ncal appliances.\nReduction in points for meats'\nshould not necessarily be interpreted 1\nas indicating a more normal supply\nof meat. The food supply is still\nprecarious and may become worse\nthan at present. Most reductions in\npoint values for foods of all kinds,\ntherefore, should be considered as\nonly temporary.\nThe reported shortage of soap is\none of the major headaches of the\ngovernment at the present moment.\nAlthough the government assures us\nthat the supply of soap and soap\nproducts i s sufficient to fill our\nneeds, the hoarding of soap is caus\ning major shortages. Clinton P. An\nderson, secretary of agriculture, in\na n effort to halt panic buying of\nsoap, released information to show\nthat the soap supply available to ci\nvilians is going to be greater rather\ntha n less than before and said there\nwas no reason to ration it. But so\nfar nothing has been able to stop\nhousewives from cleaning the gro\ncer\u2019s shelves of all available soap\nproducts.\n\nAlthough only about 30,000 men\nwill be eligible for release from ser\nvice under the new point system es\ntablished by the Navy, the plan is\nsaid to have helped strengthen mo\nrale among the older officers and\nenlisted men who can now figure on\na definite time when they can prob\nably return to civilian life.\nThe simple system established by\nthe Navy is: one point is given for\neach year of a man\u2019s age; another\npoint for each four months of serv\nice. Fifty-three to 57 points are\nneeded to apply for release, the dif\nference depending upon the branch\nof the service. Thus a man who is\n41 years old (41 points) and who\nha s been in the Navy for 4 years\n(12 points) could now apply for re\nlease if in a branch to which the 63\nquota applies.\nHOMECOMING SERVICE\nThere will be a homecoming serv\nice at Amity Baptist church the\nthird Sunday i n August. The public\nis invited and it is hoped a number\nof singers will be present. A picnic\ndinner will be served. Rev. Haskell\nSides is pastor of the church.\nDuelling for Batting Lead\ni ./T m Z sensationa bitter of the Boston Braves who\nleads the National league in batting, crosses eudgels with Goodv Rosen\not the Brooklyn Dodgers, who is following Holmes so closely that\nTommy can feel Goody's breath on his neck or may pass Holmes before\nyour paper can be delivered to you. Deiore\nVeterans\u2019 Question Box\nEd. Note: This newspaper has ar\nranged with the Washington Bureau\n;of National Weekly Service, 1616\nEye St. N. W., Washington, D. C., to\nanswer questions pertaining to serv\nicemen and veterans. These ques\ntions will be answered in this col\numn if addressed as above. No re\nplies can be made by mail, but this\npaper will print answers to all ques\n-1 tions received.\nQ.\u2014How much of the cost of edu\ncation will the government pay un\nder the provisions of the G.I. bill of\nrights?\nA.\u2014The Veterans administration\nwill pay to the educational or train\ning institution of your selection, the\ncustomary cost of tuition, and such\nlaboratory, library, infirmary and\nj similar payments as are customarily\ncharged. It may also pay for books,\nj supplies, equipment and such other\nI necessary expenses (excluding board,\nJ lodging and other living expenses and\ntravel) as are generally required by\nother students at the institution.\nSuch payments, however, shall not\nexceed SSOO for an ordinary school\nyear. The Veterans administration\nalso will provide a subsistence al\nlowance of SSO per month if you\nhave no dependents, $75 if you have.\nThis may be reduced, however, if you\nattend on a part-time basis or re\nceive compensation for work done as\na part of your training.\nQ. \u2014How much am I entitled to\ndraw under the readjustment allow\nance clause?\nA.\u2014The amount varies\u2014your local\nState Unemployment Insurance of\nf ice, Unemployment Compensation\noffice or your U. S. Employment ser\nvice office can give you the exact\namount. However, to cover tempor\nary periods of unemployment after\ndischarge you are entitled to com\npensation up to S2O a week for a\nperiod not exceeding 52 weeks, de\npending on your length of service.\nQ. \u2014I s a man entitled to muster\ning out pay if he is discharged for\nphysical disability incurred in line of\nduty?\nA.\u2014Yes, the fact that he was dis\ncharged for physical disability does\nnot make him ineligible for muster\ning out pay.\nQ. \u2014Does the United State s pay\nrent for World War cemeteries in\nEurope?\nA.\u2014The War Department informs\nus that no rent is paid to France\nYour turn... Have a Coke\n...the next move is friendly refreshment\nAmerica's outdoor living rooms are devoted to friendly living. There Jul\nthe warm invitation Have a Co\\c offers you ice-cold refreshment straight\nfrom the family icebox. There's no finer nor simpler recipe for home\nhospitality than the friendly phrase Have a Co\\c. Always have a supply\nBOTTI ED UNDER AUTHORITY OF THE COCA-COLA COMPANY BY mBEH| called by its fiiendly^bbreviatioD\nupSfpjy\u00dfH Coke'. Both mean the quality prod-\nLmcolnton Coca-Cola Bottling Company. \u2014zj uct of The coc-cok company.\nQ 1945 Th\u00ab C-C\n|or Great Britain for the land on j\nwhich our soldiers who were killed 1\nin World War I are buried. The:\nlaud was purchased for burial rights'\nin perpetuity.\nQ. \u2014Under what conditions must\nan employer give bark to a veteran\nthe job he held before entering ser\nvice?\nA.\u2014 Under the selective service\nact, the position he left must have j\nbeen a permanent one, it must still j\nbe there, he must have completed\nhis military service satisfactorily, I\nhe must still be qualified to perform\nthe duties of the position and he j\nmust apply for re-employment with- j\nin 90 days of his discharge.\nQ- \u2014How is a veteran entitled to\nunemployment compensation under\nthe G.I. bill?\nA.\u2014ls a veteran ha s reported to J\nthe Veterans Employment Branch of\nthe United States Employment serv-!\nice and has been unable to get a job,\nhe is entitled to unemployment bene\nfits of S2O a week for each week he j\nis unemployed, but for not more than j\n52 weeks.\nQ. \u2014Can a G.I. loan be obtained l\nfor payment of delinquent taxes on\nproperty already owned?\nA.\u2014Yes, proceeds of a guaranteed j\nloan may be used to pay delinquent\ntaxe s or assessments on a home al\nready owned, t Q repair a home, as\nwell as to build or buy a home.\nQ. \u2014Does the government pay the\ninterest on a G.I. guaranteed loan?\nA.\u2014The government will pay the\ninterest on the guaranteed portion\nof a loan for the first year. If the\nloan is more than $2,000, the bor\nrower will pay interest on that por\ntion above $2,000 at 4 per cent.\nI\nRevival Services\nAt White Zion\nThe annual revival services began\nMonday night, August 13. and will\ncontinue throughout the week, serv\nices each evening at 8:30 p. m. The\nKev. C. L. Grant of Lowesville is\nthe guest speaker for these services.\nA cordial invitation is extended to\nthe public to hear Rev. Mr. Grant in\nthese services.\nAlabama suggests 1,500 bream and\n100 bass in stocking an acre of fer- j\ntilized pond; 400 bream and 30 bass,!\nif not fertilized.\nMore Drilling For Oil\nTo Start Soon In N. C.\nj Raleigh, Aug. 7.\u2014State Geologist\nJ. L. Stucky said today that drilling\nfor oil in the midcoastal area of\nNorth Carolina would be resumed in\na few weeks, on lands leased by the\nCoastal Oil company. Operations will\nbe started on five sites.\nThe first w'ell, drilled near More\nhead City, was abandoned.\nThe Standard Oil Company of\nNew Jersey expects to move drilling\nequipment into the northeastern part\nof the state, to commence the first\nwell there, within six or eight weeks.\nGeophysical research will continue in\nthat area, where four companies have\nleases.\nNo announcement ha s been made\nas to location of the new well.\nBaseball!\nHickory Grove\nVs.\u2014\nHigh Shoals\nAt The\nL.H.S. Athletic\nField\nLincolnton, N. C.\nFriday Night\nAUGUST 17th At 8:30 O\u2019Clock\nADMISSION 25c\nHalve You Let A Little Life Insurance\nPolicy Rob You Os A Million\nDollars Worth Os Pleasure?\nThis Is The \u201cAir Age\u201d\nGet Wise To Yourself And Those Who\nTry To Discourage You\nJones Flying service\nAirport Lincolnton, N. C.\nPAGE FIVE\nA custard sauce, served at room\ntemperature, tastes sweeter than the\nsame sauce made into frozen cus\ntard.\nDo You Suffer\nF.om Muscular\nAches And Pains?\nSuch pains commonly referred to\nRHEUMATIC pain, cab be im>\u00ab .Tv.\"\nHowever, many people have experienced\namazingly prompt relief by taking D.M.C\nCOMPOUND No. 49. Try It today: get a\nPf c kage. CAUTION: Use only as direct*\ned. Price $3.00. Sold on a money back\nguarantee If not satisfied with results.\nTot Sale By j\nLincoln Cut Rate Drugs, Inc.,\nLincolnton, N. C.","height":"20920","width":"15114"}}
